<section xmlns="http://xml.house.gov/schemas/uslm/1.0" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="-uslm-lc:I80" id="idf68b29bb-2930-11f1-96a8-b9bd2a0a99b5" identifier="/us/usc/t46/s10319"><num value="10319">§ 10319.</num><heading> Costs of a criminal conviction</heading><content>
<p style="-uslm-lc:I11" class="indent0">In a proceeding about a seaman’s wages, if it is shown that the seaman was convicted during the voyage of an offense by a competent tribunal and sentenced by the tribunal, the court hearing the case may direct that a part of the wages due the seaman, but not more than $15, be applied to reimburse the master for costs properly incurred in procuring the conviction and sentence.</p>
</content><sourceCredit id="idf68b29bc-2930-11f1-96a8-b9bd2a0a99b5">(<ref href="/us/pl/98/89">Pub. L. 98–89</ref>, <date date="1983-08-26">Aug. 26, 1983</date>, <ref href="/us/stat/97/569">97 Stat. 569</ref>.)</sourceCredit>
